# Common Flaws AI Models Make When Writing Rust: A Comprehensive Deep-Dive

## Executive Summary

Rust presents a uniquely difficult target for AI code generation. Research reveals that **40%+ of compilation errors** produced by LLMs stem from ownership and borrowing violations, **60%+ of faults are semantic** (the code compiles but does the wrong thing), and **19.7% of suggested crate dependencies are hallucinated** packages that do not exist on crates.io. Baseline pass rates for AI-generated Rust hover around **~29%**, with **58.5% of LLMs unable to generate immediately usable Rust code**. In production settings, AI-authored pull requests contain roughly **1.7x more issues** than human-authored ones. This document catalogs 12 categories of failure, provides concrete bad/good code examples, explains root causes, and recommends a detection toolchain.

---

