## 9. Cargo and Dependency Issues

### 9.1 Hallucinated Crates

**Description:** Research found that **19.7% of packages suggested by LLMs do not exist on crates.io**. Furthermore, **43% of hallucinated package names are repeated across multiple queries**, indicating systematic rather than random hallucination. This is a supply-chain security risk: an attacker could register the hallucinated package name and inject malicious code.

**Bad code (Cargo.toml):**

```toml
[dependencies]
rust-crypto = "0.3"       # exists but unmaintained and vulnerable
serde_yaml2 = "1.0"       # hallucinated: does not exist
tokio-utils = "0.7"       # hallucinated: the real crate is tokio-util (no 's')
http-client = "2.0"       # hallucinated or name collision
```

**Good code (Cargo.toml):**

```toml
[dependencies]
# Verify each crate at https://crates.io before adding
ring = "0.17"              # actively maintained crypto library
serde_yaml = "0.9"         # real crate, correct name
tokio-util = "0.7"         # correct name (no trailing 's')
reqwest = "0.12"           # well-known HTTP client
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** The AI interpolates plausible crate names from patterns it has seen (e.g., `tokio-util` becomes `tokio-utils`). It cannot verify whether a crate exists at generation time. The 43% repeat rate suggests certain naming patterns are systematically hallucinated.

**Impact:** Build failures at best, supply-chain attacks at worst. If an attacker registers `tokio-utils` on crates.io with malicious code, every project that trusts the AI's suggestion is compromised.

**Detection and mitigation:** Verify every crate on [crates.io](https://crates.io) before adding it to `Cargo.toml`. Run `cargo audit` to check for known vulnerabilities in dependencies. Use `cargo-deny` to enforce an allow-list of approved crates.

---

### 9.2 Outdated Crate Versions and APIs

**Description:** The AI references crate versions and API surfaces from its training data, which may be months or years out of date. This is especially common with fast-moving crates like `reqwest`, `tokio`, and `axum`.

**Bad code:**

```rust
// Using the old blocking reqwest API in an async context
fn fetch_data(url: &str) -> Result<String, reqwest::Error> {
    let body = reqwest::get(url)?.text()?; // reqwest::get was blocking in 0.9
    Ok(body)
}
```

**Good code:**

```rust
// Modern async reqwest API
async fn fetch_data(url: &str) -> Result<String, reqwest::Error> {
    let body = reqwest::get(url).await?.text().await?;
    Ok(body)
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** The model's training data includes code written against older versions of popular crates. It cannot check the current crates.io documentation at generation time.

**Impact:** Compilation errors or subtle behavioral differences when the generated code is used with current crate versions.

**Detection and mitigation:** `cargo update` and `cargo check` will surface version incompatibilities. Always verify API usage against the current documentation on [docs.rs](https://docs.rs).

