## 11. Async Rust Mistakes

### 11.1 Task Cancellation Safety

**Description:** In Rust's async model, a future can be dropped (cancelled) at any `.await` point. The AI writes cleanup logic after an await point, assuming it will always execute. If the task is cancelled at the await point, the cleanup is silently skipped.

**Bad code:**

```rust
async fn process_job(job: Job, metrics: &Metrics) -> Result<()> {
    metrics.record_start(&job);
    let result = do_work(&job).await?; // if cancelled here...
    metrics.record_completion(&job);   // ...this never runs
    save_result(result).await?;        // ...and this never runs
    Ok(())
}
```

**Good code:**

```rust
use scopeguard::defer;

async fn process_job(job: Job, metrics: &Metrics) -> Result<()> {
    metrics.record_start(&job);
    defer! {
        metrics.record_completion_or_cancellation(&job);
    }
    let result = do_work(&job).await?;
    save_result(result).await?;
    Ok(())
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Task cancellation is a concept unique to Rust's async model (and similar to Go's context cancellation, but enforced differently). The AI writes sequential code assuming every line will execute, which is only true in synchronous code.

**Impact:** Resource leaks, inconsistent metrics, and dangling state. In systems with external resources (database connections, file locks), this can cause resource exhaustion.

**Detection and mitigation:** Use `scopeguard::defer!` or implement `Drop` for cleanup that must run regardless of cancellation. Review all code after `.await` points to verify cancellation safety.

---

### 11.2 Recreating Futures in `select!` Loops

**Description:** The AI uses `tokio::select!` inside a loop, creating new futures on each iteration. This discards any buffered data or partial progress from the previous iteration of the future.

**Bad code:**

```rust
use tokio::io::AsyncReadExt;

async fn read_with_timeout(stream: &mut TcpStream) -> Result<Vec<u8>> {
    let mut buf = vec![0u8; 1024];
    loop {
        tokio::select! {
            result = stream.read(&mut buf) => {
                // `stream.read()` future is recreated each iteration
                // Any partially buffered data from a previous read is lost
                return Ok(buf[..result?].to_vec());
            }
            _ = tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_secs(5)) => {
                println!("Heartbeat");
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Good code:**

```rust
use tokio::io::AsyncReadExt;
use std::pin::pin;

async fn read_with_timeout(stream: &mut TcpStream) -> Result<Vec<u8>> {
    let mut buf = vec![0u8; 1024];
    let mut read_future = pin!(stream.read(&mut buf));
    loop {
        tokio::select! {
            result = &mut read_future => {
                return Ok(buf[..result?].to_vec());
            }
            _ = tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_secs(5)) => {
                println!("Heartbeat");
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** The `select!` macro's semantics are subtle: branches that are not selected are dropped. The AI does not recognize that recreating a future on each loop iteration means losing progress.

**Impact:** Lost data, infinite loops, and incorrect behavior that is extremely difficult to debug because it depends on timing.

**Detection and mitigation:** Manual review of all `select!` loops. Any future created inside the loop body that is not intended to be restarted should be moved outside the loop and referenced with `&mut`.

---

### 11.3 Future Progress Starvation

**Description:** The AI processes items sequentially in an accept loop, awaiting each item to completion before accepting the next. This means the server can only handle one connection at a time.

**Bad code:**

```rust
async fn run_server(listener: TcpListener) {
    loop {
        let (stream, _) = listener.accept().await.unwrap();
        handle_connection(stream).await; // blocks the accept loop!
    }
}
```

**Good code:**

```rust
async fn run_server(listener: TcpListener) {
    loop {
        let (stream, _) = listener.accept().await.unwrap();
        tokio::spawn(async move {
            handle_connection(stream).await;
        });
    }
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** The sequential version is simpler and mirrors synchronous server code. The AI does not recognize that `.await` in an accept loop serializes all connection handling.

**Impact:** The server processes one connection at a time, defeating the purpose of async I/O.

**Detection and mitigation:** Code review should verify that accept loops spawn tasks for each connection. Load testing will immediately reveal the problem.

---

### 11.4 Holding RAII Guards Across Await Points

**Description:** Beyond locks (covered in Section 6.1), the AI holds other RAII guards (database connection pool checkouts, tracing spans, temp file handles) across await points. When the task is cancelled or the await takes a long time, the resource is held far longer than intended.

**Bad code:**

```rust
async fn query_database(pool: &Pool) -> Result<Vec<Row>> {
    let conn = pool.get().await?; // checks out connection from pool
    let rows = conn.query("SELECT * FROM large_table").await?;
    // Connection held during entire query -- if query is slow,
    // pool may be exhausted for other tasks
    process_rows(&rows).await?; // still holding the connection!
    Ok(rows)
}
```

**Good code:**

```rust
async fn query_database(pool: &Pool) -> Result<Vec<Row>> {
    let rows = {
        let conn = pool.get().await?;
        conn.query("SELECT * FROM large_table").await?
        // connection returned to pool here when `conn` is dropped
    };
    process_rows(&rows).await?;
    Ok(rows)
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** The AI does not track the scope of RAII guards or reason about when destructors run. It writes code in a straight-line fashion without considering resource lifetimes.

**Impact:** Resource pool exhaustion, connection starvation, and cascading failures under load.

**Detection and mitigation:** Clippy's `await_holding_lock` lint catches mutex guards. For other RAII guards, manual review is necessary. Scope guards into explicit blocks to control their lifetime.

