## 12. General AI Code Quality

### 12.1 Excessive Comments

**Description:** AI-generated code contains verbose, obvious comments on 90-100% of lines. These comments restate what the code already says, add noise, and obscure the code's intent.

**Bad code:**

```rust
// Define a function to calculate the sum of two numbers
fn add(a: i32, b: i32) -> i32 {
    // Add a and b together
    let result = a + b; // Store the result of the addition
    // Return the result
    result // Return the sum
}
```

**Good code:**

```rust
fn add(a: i32, b: i32) -> i32 {
    a + b
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** Training data includes heavily commented tutorial code. The AI also uses comments as "filler" to demonstrate understanding, similar to how a student might over-explain an exam answer.

**Impact:** Reduced readability, increased maintenance burden, and a signal to reviewers that the code is AI-generated. In some organizations, excessive comments trigger additional review scrutiny.

**Detection and mitigation:** Code review should remove comments that restate the code. A team style guide should specify commenting standards.

---

### 12.2 Refactoring Avoidance

**Description:** The AI appends new code to the end of a function or file instead of restructuring the existing code to accommodate the new functionality. This leads to growing functions, duplicated logic, and increasing complexity.

**Bad code:**

```rust
fn process_order(order: &Order) -> Result<()> {
    // Original 50 lines of order processing...
    validate_order(order)?;
    calculate_tax(order)?;
    apply_discount(order)?;
    save_order(order)?;

    // AI was asked to add logging -- appends at the end instead of integrating
    println!("Order processed: {}", order.id);
    println!("Tax: {}", order.tax);
    println!("Discount: {}", order.discount);
    println!("Total: {}", order.total);

    // AI was asked to add metrics -- appends again
    METRICS.orders_processed.inc();
    METRICS.revenue.add(order.total);

    Ok(())
}
```

**Good code:**

```rust
fn process_order(order: &Order) -> Result<()> {
    validate_order(order)?;
    calculate_tax(order)?;
    apply_discount(order)?;
    save_order(order)?;

    log_order(order);
    record_order_metrics(order);

    Ok(())
}

fn log_order(order: &Order) {
    info!(
        order_id = %order.id,
        tax = order.tax,
        discount = order.discount,
        total = order.total,
        "Order processed"
    );
}

fn record_order_metrics(order: &Order) {
    METRICS.orders_processed.inc();
    METRICS.revenue.add(order.total);
}
```

**Why AI makes this mistake:** The AI generates code incrementally and does not "step back" to consider the overall structure. It treats each request as an append operation rather than an integration task. Restructuring existing code requires understanding the full context, which is more expensive for the model than appending.

**Impact:** Functions grow unboundedly, code becomes harder to test in isolation, and duplicated logic creates maintenance hazards.

**Detection and mitigation:** Code review should enforce function length limits and the single responsibility principle. Clippy's `too_many_lines` lint can flag excessively long functions.

